// FEATURE REQUEST: "Typed Codegen Data Structures" [BLOCKER]
// The old approach used global callback-based routing (AvoCustomDestination protocol
// with make/logEvent/setUserProperties callbacks configured at init time).
// This new approach generates well-defined, typed data structures per event (structs
// in the App layer) that conform to the AvoEvent protocol. Each struct exposes
// typed properties and a verify() method — no callbacks needed at the event level.
// The developer creates a struct, calls verify(), reads .properties, and passes
// the data to their own analytics library.
//
// FEATURE REQUEST: "Event Verify Method in Codegen" [Must Have]
// The AvoEvent protocol below includes `func verify() throws`. Each generated
// event struct implements this method with its specific validation rules (min/max
// assertions). The verify() method is pure — it throws AvoVerificationError on
// failure with accumulated violation messages. No side effects, no env guards.
// This enables:
// - Internal library use: call verify() before sending to catch bad data
// - Reporting: catch the error and route to your own reporting infra
// - Unit testing: assert that verify() throws/doesn't throw for given inputs
//
// FEATURE REQUEST: "Automated JSON Key Formatting" [Must Have]
// Name mapping is handled in the event struct's `properties` computed property.
// Each destination can have different key names for the same logical property.
// The codegen generates the correct key names per destination based on the
// workspace configuration. See AppEvents.swift for examples of:
// - Global name mapping (all destinations get a renamed key)
// - Per-destination name mapping (only specific destinations get renamed keys)
// - snake_case formatting applied at generation time
//
// FEATURE REQUEST: "TypeScript Tracking Objects" [Must Have]
// While this demo is Swift, the same architectural pattern applies to TypeScript.
// Instead of callback-based routing, TS codegen would return typed tracking objects
// with name + properties. The AvoEventOut equivalent in TS would be:
//   interface AvoEventOut { name: string; properties: Record<string, unknown> }
// And each event function would return Record<string, AvoEventOut> keyed by destination.
